f=Cybersecurity/cortex/marketplace/threat-hunting/SKILL.md · in=Proactive, hypothesis-driven search signs compromise existing detection rules missed. Unlike detection engineering (which waits alerts) incident response (which reacts confirmed incidents), threat hunting actively looks unknown subtle indicators, novel techniques, evidence adversaries who evaded preventive controls. **Sourced from:** mukul975 Anthropic-Cybersecurity-Skills collection (817 skills, MITRE ATT&CK NIST CSF mapped). Individual hunting playbooks selected executed hunting hypothesis. · p=Detection rules reactive they find what they written detect. Threat hunting finds what rules missed: novel attacker techniques, subtle indicators compromise, evidence adversary presence didn't trigger alert. It's difference between waiting alarm off actively checking someone already inside. · wu=Scheduled hunt cadence (e.g., weekly monthly)., New threat intelligence about specific technique actor group., Post-incident check related compromises discovered., After major infrastructure changes verify new vulnerabilities introduced., "Let's look X," "hunt signs Y," "are compromised." · h3:Step Formulate Hypothesis=Start clear, testable hypothesis based on: · h3:Step Formulate Hypothesis=**Threat intelligence** new CVE, active campaign, emerging TTP, **Internal trends** increase certain alert types, unusual network patterns, **Post-incident lessons** "if adversary here, what else they done?", **Frameworks** MITRE ATT&CK techniques currently covered detection rules · h3:Step Identify Data Sources=Determine what data contain evidence hypothesis: · h3:Step Identify Data Sources=Endpoint logs (EDR, sysmon, osquery), Network logs (flows, DNS, proxy, Zeek), Cloud logs (CloudTrail, audit logs, access logs), Identity logs (authentication, directory changes), Application logs · h3:Step Execute Hunt=Run queries, scripts, tools against identified data sources: · h3:Step Execute Hunt=Use mukul975 collection's specific playbook technique hunted (BloodHound Active Directory, Velociraptor endpoint, Falco runtime, Scapy network), Document query results, Note any baseline behaviors context · h3:Step Analyze Findings=For each finding, determine: · h3:Step Analyze Findings=**Benign** expected behavior, known baseline, **Suspicious** unusual clearly malicious; flag monitoring, **Malicious** confirmed indicator compromise escalate security-incident-response · h3:Step 5 — Operationalize=Malicious findings incident response, Suspicious findings new detection rule monitoring enhancement, findings document negative result (absence evidence evidence absence), hunt produces: hypothesis, data sources, queries, findings, recommendations · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| Scenario \| Tool/Technique \| What to Look For \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\|---\|---\|---\| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| AD privilege escalation \| BloodHound CE \| Unexpected Kerberoastable accounts, DCSync paths, ACL abuse paths \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| Lateral movement \| Velociraptor fleet hunt \| Remote service creation, WMI/WinRM usage, PsExec execution \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| Container compromise \| Falco runtime detection \| Unexpected shell in container, mount namespace escape, suspicious syscalls \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| Credential theft \| Kerberoasting detection \| Unusual TGS-REQ counts, service account with SPN but no business need \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| ADCS abuse \| Certipy techniques \| Unusual certificate requests, ESC1-ESC8 indicators \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| DPAPI abuse \| DPAPI forensic analysis \| Unexpected DPAPI backup key access, credential file decryption \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| Network beaconing \| Scapy/Zeek analysis \| Periodic outbound connections, unusual protocols, suspicious DNS \| · h2:Common Hunting Scenarios (from mukul975 collection)=\| Kubernetes RBAC abuse \| K8s audit log analysis \| Unusual role binding, sensitive resource access from unknown service accounts \| · of=`## Threat Hunt: [hypothesis] — [date] \· Hypothesis: [what we looked for and why] \· Data sources: [logs/tools queried] \· Playbook: [mukul975 collection — specific skill used] \· Findings:` · pr=**Hypothesis-driven, random.** hunt without hypothesis noise. **Document negative.** hunt finds nothing still valuable means hypothesis didn't materialize. **Findings become detection rules.** Suspicious findings don't warrant trigger new detection rule. **Hunt what you see; flag what you can't.** data test hypothesis doesn't exist, that's logging gap flag warden. **Coordinate incident response.** malicious finding escalates full IR; threat hunting itself contain. · f=EDR endpoint logs hunt network logs cloud audit logs only, labeled "limited visibility EDR.", mukul975 collection installed general hunting methodology applies; reference MITRE ATT&CK manually hypothesis generation., Logging gap hypothesis flag gap, recommend log source adoption, hunt available data. · b:with Other Skills=**detection-engineering** (sibling): hunt findings don't meet threshold become new detection rules., **security-monitoring** (sibling): hunts produce leads enter monitoring triage queue., **security-incident-response** (sibling): malicious hunt findings escalate directly IR., **bastion**: infrastructure-focused hunts (container, cloud) coordinate bastion's infra scope., **warden**: logging gaps blind spots identified hunts register risks.